    {
      "title": "The Masculine Pronoun هُوَ",
      "titleArabic": "الضمير المذكر",
      "content": [
        "The pronoun هُوَ (huwa) means 'he' and is used for masculine singular nouns, including people and things. In Arabic, all nouns have grammatical gender.",
        "When referring to a masculine noun mentioned earlier in the conversation, use هُوَ. This includes objects like 'the book' (الكِتَابُ) which is grammatically masculine."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "هُوَ (he/it) is used for all masculine singular nouns",
        "Arabic nouns are either masculine or feminine - there is no neutral gender",
        "Use هُوَ to refer back to masculine nouns, including objects"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "هُوَ طَالِبٌ", "english": "He is a student" },
        { "arabic": "هُوَ مُدَرِّسٌ", "english": "He is a teacher" },
        { "arabic": "مَنْ هُوَ؟ هُوَ طَبِيبٌ", "english": "Who is he? He is a doctor" },
        { "arabic": "هَذَا رَجُلٌ وَهُوَ مُهَنْدِسٌ", "english": "This is a man and he is an engineer" }
      ]
    }
  ],
